---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import OrganicFrame from "../../components/OrganicFrame.astro";
import SectionDivider from "../../components/SectionDivider.astro";
import NumericCartouche from "../../components/NumericCartouche.astro";
import ChapterRail from "../../components/ChapterRail.astro";
import ChapterTitle from "../../components/ChapterTitle.astro";
import ChapterPlate from "../../components/ChapterPlate.astro";
import Interlude from "../../components/Interlude.astro";
import OrnatePopupTrigger from "../../components/OrnatePopupTrigger.astro";
import OrnatePopupContent from "../../components/OrnatePopupContent.astro";
import ComparisonPlate from "../../components/ComparisonPlate.astro";
---

<Layout title="Ornaments — dev" description="QA page for ornament primitives">
  <ChapterRail />

  <h1>Ornaments</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Internal QA page for the Mucha's Notebook ornament library.
  </p>

  <h2>OrganicFrame with SubjectMarker</h2>
  <p>Three OrganicFrames, each with a different subject. The marker in the
  top-right corner identifies the subject at a glance.</p>

  <OrganicFrame subject="water">
    <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>Water.</strong> Teal droplet in the corner.
    Use on the water bracket chart, the water-vs-golf comparison, and anything
    measuring billion gallons.</p>
  </OrganicFrame>

  <OrganicFrame subject="electricity">
    <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>Electricity.</strong> Sage leaf in the corner.
    Use on annual TWh, the trajectory charts, household equivalents, the watt
    scale primer.</p>
  </OrganicFrame>

  <OrganicFrame subject="carbon">
    <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>Carbon.</strong> Rust diamond in the corner.
    Use on the hourly hero, training-vs-inference, and CO₂ comparison cards.</p>
  </OrganicFrame>

  <h2>Ornate OrganicFrame (Phase 2e.1)</h2>
  <p>The ornate variant adds botanical side accents climbing the inside of
  the frame. Pass <code>sideLeft</code> and/or <code>sideRight</code>. The
  frame grows its horizontal padding automatically so content doesn't
  collide with the accents.</p>

  <OrganicFrame subject="electricity" sideLeft>
    <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>Left side only.</strong> Wheat-and-leaves
    motif climbing the inside-left edge. Used on charts that want a single
    botanical accent — most home-page infographics.</p>
  </OrganicFrame>

  <OrganicFrame subject="water" sideLeft sideRight>
    <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>Both sides.</strong> Wheat on the left,
    floral spray on the right. Used on the most ceremonial chart of a chapter
    — typically the headline plate.</p>
  </OrganicFrame>

  <OrganicFrame subject="carbon" sideRight>
    <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>Right side only.</strong> Floral motif
    climbing the inside-right. Less common — for charts whose left side
    wants to be clean.</p>
  </OrganicFrame>

  <h2>NumericCartouche</h2>
  <p>Headline figure treatment. Display-size Cardo number flanked by small
  subject-colored almond flourishes. Used at the top of bar charts to surface
  the chart's most consequential figure before the bars themselves are read.</p>

  <NumericCartouche
    value="460"
    unit="TWh"
    subject="electricity"
    caption="Global data centers, 2024"
  />

  <NumericCartouche
    value="500–700"
    unit="billion gallons"
    subject="water"
    caption="Global data-center water, 2025 (including electricity-generation)"
  />

  <NumericCartouche
    value="8.4–27"
    unit="million tCO₂"
    subject="carbon"
    caption="All AI inference, 2024"
  />

  <h2>Ornate NumericCartouche (Phase 2e.1)</h2>
  <p>The ornate variant wraps the value in an Art Nouveau cartouche frame
  asset. Pass <code>ornate</code>. Suitable for hero figures within a chapter
  rather than every bar chart.</p>

  <NumericCartouche
    value="460"
    unit="TWh"
    subject="electricity"
    caption="Global data centers, 2024"
    ornate
  />

  <NumericCartouche
    value="500–700"
    unit="billion gallons"
    subject="water"
    caption="Global data-center water, 2025"
    ornate
  />

  <NumericCartouche
    value="8.4–27"
    unit="million tCO₂"
    subject="carbon"
    caption="All AI inference, 2024"
    ornate
  />

  <h2>ChapterTitle (Phase 3.5 refactor)</h2>
  <p>Chapter-opening header used on the home page. Cardo small-caps
  Roman-numeral kicker, Cardo display title (no dropcap), a plain hairline
  ornament rule, optional sage-italic headline sentence. First example
  carries the finalized headline; the other five show the title without a
  headline so the no-headline variant gets exercised.</p>

  <ChapterTitle
    number={1}
    title="The Hour"
    headline="One hour, one person: where most claims wander furthest from the data."
  />

  <ChapterTitle number={2} title="The Year" />
  <ChapterTitle number={3} title="The Water" />
  <ChapterTitle number={4} title="The Trajectory" />
  <ChapterTitle number={5} title="In Equivalents" />
  <ChapterTitle number={6} title="Training vs. Inference" />

  <h2>ChapterPlate (Phase 3.5)</h2>
  <p>Magazine-spread asymmetric layout for a chapter's headline plate.
  Annotation column on the left (30%) carries the small-caps kicker, the
  ornate <code>NumericCartouche</code>, a brief italic gloss, and the
  subject motif. Chart canvas on the right (70%) renders into the slot.
  Below ~720px the columns stack.</p>

  <ChapterPlate
    subject="electricity"
    kicker="AI'S YEAR, IN CONTEXT"
    value="30–80"
    unit="TWh"
    caption="AI IN DATA CENTERS, 2024"
    italic="Even at the top of its range, the shortest bar on the chart."
  >
    <div class="canvas-stub" aria-hidden="true">
      Chart canvas (slot) — Infographic SVG renders here.
    </div>
  </ChapterPlate>

  <h2>Interlude (Phase 3.5)</h2>
  <p>Three-column mid-chapter pause: two ornate cartouches flanking a
  centered italic line. Used inside chapters IV (between the DC and
  AI-share trajectories) and V (between the watt-scale primer and the
  household equivalents). Below ~720px the three cells stack.</p>

  <Interlude
    leftSubject="electricity"
    leftValue="485"
    leftUnit="TWh"
    leftCaption="DATA CENTERS, 2025"
    italic="The line bent because data centers got bigger. They got bigger because of AI."
    rightSubject="electricity"
    rightValue="300"
    rightUnit="TWh"
    rightCaption="AI BY 2030, CENTRAL CASE"
  />

  <h2>OrnatePopup (Phase 3.5+) — bloom-from-click dialog</h2>
  <p>OrnatePopup mounts once in Layout.astro. Triggers pair with content
  templates via matching ids. Click any of the four below to verify the
  bloom animation, focus trap, ESC dismissal, and backdrop close.</p>

  <div class="popup-trigger-row">
    <OrnatePopupTrigger popupId="qa-popup-prose" as="prose">
      An inline prose trigger
    </OrnatePopupTrigger>
    <OrnatePopupTrigger popupId="qa-popup-bare" as="bare">
      <span style="border: 1px dashed var(--rule); padding: 0.4rem 0.8rem; border-radius: 4px;">Bare button trigger</span>
    </OrnatePopupTrigger>
  </div>

  <div class="popup-trigger-row">
    <div style="max-width: 280px;">
      <OrnatePopupTrigger popupId="qa-popup-cartouche" as="cartouche">
        <NumericCartouche
          value="42"
          unit="QA units"
          caption="A CARTOUCHE TRIGGER"
          subject="electricity"
          ornate
        />
      </OrnatePopupTrigger>
    </div>
    <div style="max-width: 320px;">
      <OrnatePopupTrigger popupId="qa-popup-card" as="card">
        <OrganicFrame subject="carbon" sideLeft>
          <p style="margin: 0; text-align: center;">
            <strong>A card trigger.</strong><br/>Hover for the lift.
          </p>
        </OrganicFrame>
      </OrnatePopupTrigger>
    </div>
  </div>

  <OrnatePopupContent popupId="qa-popup-prose">
    <p class="popup-kicker">QA</p>
    <h2 id="popup-title-qa-popup-prose">Prose trigger</h2>
    <p>This popup opens from inline prose. The trigger is styled like a soft accented underline so it reads as interactive without disturbing the paragraph rhythm.</p>
    <p class="popup-sources">QA only.</p>
  </OrnatePopupContent>
  <OrnatePopupContent popupId="qa-popup-bare">
    <p class="popup-kicker">QA</p>
    <h2 id="popup-title-qa-popup-bare">Bare trigger</h2>
    <p>The bare variant carries no styling itself — the wrapped element renders as-is. Good for wrapping anything custom.</p>
    <p class="popup-sources">QA only.</p>
  </OrnatePopupContent>
  <OrnatePopupContent popupId="qa-popup-cartouche">
    <p class="popup-kicker">QA</p>
    <h2 id="popup-title-qa-popup-cartouche">Cartouche trigger</h2>
    <p>Wrap a NumericCartouche. The chapter plates use this variant. The cartouche art reads as the headline; the popup carries the source detail.</p>
    <p class="popup-sources">QA only.</p>
  </OrnatePopupContent>
  <OrnatePopupContent popupId="qa-popup-card">
    <p class="popup-kicker">QA</p>
    <h2 id="popup-title-qa-popup-card">Card trigger</h2>
    <p>Wrap an OrganicFrame. The /comparisons herbarium uses this variant. Hovering lifts the card 2px on desktop; the hover is suppressed below 720px.</p>
    <p class="popup-sources">QA only.</p>
  </OrnatePopupContent>

  <h2>ComparisonPlate (Phase 5 redesign)</h2>
  <p>Renders a single comparison plate. The whole plate is a card trigger;
  the front carries title + unit caption + an "Open detail →" affordance.</p>

  <div class="plate-grid-stub">
    <ComparisonPlate
      id="qa-cmp"
      title="QA · sample comparison vs. AI"
      unitCaption="Sample units per year"
      subject="water"
      popupId="qa-popup-comparison"
    />
    <ComparisonPlate
      id="qa-cmp-2"
      title="QA · second sample comparison"
      unitCaption="Sample units per year"
      subject="carbon"
      popupId="qa-popup-comparison-2"
    />
  </div>

  <OrnatePopupContent popupId="qa-popup-comparison">
    <p class="popup-kicker">Comparison</p>
    <h2 id="popup-title-qa-popup-comparison">QA · sample comparison vs. AI</h2>
    <p>The popup-driven /comparisons design puts the full detail behind a click. The grid plate carries title + unit caption; the popup carries summary + RangeBar + sources.</p>
    <p class="popup-sources">QA only.</p>
  </OrnatePopupContent>
  <OrnatePopupContent popupId="qa-popup-comparison-2">
    <p class="popup-kicker">Comparison</p>
    <h2 id="popup-title-qa-popup-comparison-2">QA · second sample comparison</h2>
    <p>Second sample so the 2-column grid layout is visible at desktop widths.</p>
    <p class="popup-sources">QA only.</p>
  </OrnatePopupContent>

  <h2>SectionDividers in chapter order</h2>
  <p>How the dividers will read as the reader scrolls the home page.</p>

  <SectionDivider motif="carbon" />
  <p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic; color: var(--ink-faint); margin-top: 0;">
    The Hour
  </p>
  <SectionDivider motif="wheat" />
  <p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic; color: var(--ink-faint); margin-top: 0;">
    The Year
  </p>
  <SectionDivider motif="water" />
  <p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic; color: var(--ink-faint); margin-top: 0;">
    The Water
  </p>
  <SectionDivider motif="vine" />
  <p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic; color: var(--ink-faint); margin-top: 0;">
    The Trajectory
  </p>
  <SectionDivider motif="wheat" />
  <p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic; color: var(--ink-faint); margin-top: 0;">
    In Equivalents
  </p>
  <SectionDivider motif="carbon" />
  <p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic; color: var(--ink-faint); margin-top: 0;">
    Training vs. Inference
  </p>

  <h2>ChapterRail</h2>
  <p>Six-dot reading-progress widget for the right margin of the home page.
  Visible to the right of this page at viewport widths ≥ 980px. Quiet rings
  at rest; the active dot fills with its chapter's subject color. Hover or
  tab onto a dot for the chapter title; click to scroll to that chapter.</p>
  <p>Below are six tall scroll-dummy sections with the matching ids
  (<code>the-hour</code> through <code>training-vs-inference</code>) so the
  scroll-spy and tooltip behaviors can be exercised end-to-end. The active
  dot should update as you scroll through them.</p>

  <section id="the-hour" class="rail-dummy">
    <h3>The Hour</h3>
    <p class="dummy-note">Dummy section. Active dot should fill rust.</p>
  </section>
  <section id="the-year" class="rail-dummy">
    <h3>The Year</h3>
    <p class="dummy-note">Dummy section. Active dot should fill sage.</p>
  </section>
  <section id="the-water" class="rail-dummy">
    <h3>The Water</h3>
    <p class="dummy-note">Dummy section. Active dot should fill teal.</p>
  </section>
  <section id="the-trajectory" class="rail-dummy">
    <h3>The Trajectory</h3>
    <p class="dummy-note">Dummy section. Active dot should fill sage.</p>
  </section>
  <section id="in-equivalents" class="rail-dummy">
    <h3>In Equivalents</h3>
    <p class="dummy-note">Dummy section. Active dot should fill sage.</p>
  </section>
  <section id="training-vs-inference" class="rail-dummy">
    <h3>Training vs. Inference</h3>
    <p class="dummy-note">Dummy section. Active dot should fill rust.</p>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .rail-dummy {
    min-height: 70vh;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
    padding: var(--space-7) 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    justify-content: center;
  }
  .rail-dummy h3 {
    margin: 0;
    text-align: center;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .dummy-note {
    text-align: center;
    color: var(--ink-faint);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    margin: var(--space-3) 0 0;
  }
  .canvas-stub {
    min-height: 220px;
    border: 1px dashed var(--rule);
    border-radius: 6px;
    background: rgba(122, 140, 106, 0.05);
    color: var(--ink-faint);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    padding: var(--space-5);
    text-align: center;
  }
  .popup-trigger-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--space-5);
    align-items: center;
    margin: var(--space-5) 0;
  }
  .plate-grid-stub {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-5);
    margin: var(--space-5) 0;
  }
  @media (min-width: 720px) {
    .plate-grid-stub {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
